{"questionId":"27985","questionHtml":"<p>Find the <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>x</mi></math>-coordinate of point <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtext>E</mtext></math> for the largest area of the square foundation of building <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtext>EFGH</mtext></math>.</p>","markschemeHtml":"<p>width of the square is <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>70</mn><mo>-</mo><mi>x</mi></math>&nbsp; <strong>OR</strong>&nbsp; the length of the square is&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mrow><mo>-</mo><msup><mi>x</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></mrow><mn>50</mn></mfrac><mo>+</mo><mn>2</mn><mi>x</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>30</mn></math>&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<em><strong>(M1)</strong></em></p>\n<p><strong><br>Note:</strong> Award <em><strong>(M1)</strong></em> for&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>70</mn><mo>-</mo><mi>x</mi></math>&nbsp;seen anywhere.&nbsp;Accept&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mrow><mo>-</mo><msup><mi>x</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></mrow><mn>50</mn></mfrac><mo>+</mo><mn>2</mn><mi>x</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>30</mn></math>&nbsp;but only if this expression is explicitly identified as a dimension of the square.</p>\n<p><br>in term of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>x</mi></math>, equating the length to the width <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtext>ED</mtext></math>&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<em><strong>(M1)</strong></em></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mrow><mo>-</mo><msup><mi>x</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></mrow><mn>50</mn></mfrac><mo>+</mo><mn>2</mn><mi>x</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>30</mn><mo>=</mo><mn>70</mn><mo>-</mo><mi>x</mi></math></p>\n<p>(<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>x</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>14</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>7920</mn><mo>…</mo></math>&nbsp; or&nbsp;&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>135</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>21</mn></math>)</p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><mrow><mi>x</mi><mo>=</mo></mrow></mfenced><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mn>14</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>8</mn><mo> </mo><mtext>m</mtext><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mfenced><mrow><mn>14</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>7920</mn><mo>…</mo></mrow></mfenced></math>&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<em><strong>A1</strong></em></p>\n<p><br><strong>Note:</strong> Award <em><strong>M0M0A0</strong> </em>for an unsupported answer of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>15</mn></math>. Award at most <em><strong>M1M0A0</strong> </em>for an approach which leads to <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>A</mi><mo>'</mo><mfenced><mi>x</mi></mfenced><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn></math>. This will lead to a square base which extends beyond the east boundary of the property. Similar for any solution where <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtext>F</mtext></math> is not on the northern boundary, or <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtext>GH</mtext></math> is not on the east boundary.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><em><strong>[3 marks</strong></em><em><strong>]</strong></em></p>","meta":{"questionId":"27985","referenceCode":"22N.2.SL.TZ0.5d.i","subjectId":"51-dp-mathematics-applications-and-interpretation","title":"Find the x-coordinate of point E for the largest area of the square foundation of building EFGH.","paper":"2","level":"SL","questionNumber":"d.i","marksAvailable":"[Maximum mark: 3]","breadcrumbLabels":["Topic 5—Calculus","Topic 5—Calculus","SL 5.7—Optimisation"],"memberSectionIds":[],"sectionOrders":{}}}